{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"34f83c26-85e5-44b8-ad7f-e069aff5e7fb","content":"Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, so there's nothing to migrate on that front. Good news.\n\nHowever, the pattern of manually spinning up `Thread` objects is outdated for .NET 8. Here's the modern equivalent using `Task` / `Parallel`:\n\n```csharp\npublic class SimpleWorker\n{\n    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)\n    {\n        await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>\n        {\n            await Task.Run(() => Process(item), ct);\n        });\n    }\n\n    private void Process(WorkItem item)\n    {\n        Thread.Sleep(100); // consider await Task.Delay(100) if truly async\n        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points for your migration:**\n\n| Concern | Guidance |\n|---|---|\n| **`Thread.Abort`** | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8. Use `CancellationToken` for cooperative cancellation instead. |\n| **Raw `Thread` + `Join`** | Replace with `Task.Run` / `Parallel.ForEachAsync` — better threadpool utilization. |\n| **Cancellation** | Pass a `CancellationToken` and check `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `Process`. |\n\nIf you have `Thread.Abort` elsewhere in your codebase, the fix is always the same: replace with **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationTokenSource` + `CancellationToken`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"78b54a9d-58f5-4b81-a99c-966d94ed07e8","outputTokens":384,"requestId":"D006:170FAA:1A5D2B5:1DD076A:69E8235D"},"id":"347ee91b-1346-4eae-94ab-8b6f568e57d4","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:24:52.633Z","parentId":"84ab18e5-8ca4-4583-9330-48181bd4353f"}
